description:
Large Sovereign Wealth Fund seeking to expand its real estate investment focus in New York with the addition of an experienced candidate at the Senior Associate/Vice President level in their New York office.


Client Details

Large Sovereign Wealth Fund with over $250 Billion USD AUM.

The SWF is currently seeking to expand its real estate investment functions based in New York with the addition of an experienced candidate (s) at Senior Associate to Vice President Level to the New York office. The successful candidate will be tasked with covering global alternative Investment markets.

Description

The Real Estate Portfolio Manager will be responsible for:


Identifying and screening potential real estate investment opportunities;

Conducting Preliminary assessment, financial analysis and business due diligence for direct & co investment and fund of funds investment opportunities;

Managing and updating real estate fund information, conducting due diligence on fund investments;

Writing due diligence reports and follow-up notes on existing and potential GPs;

Monitoring on-going real estate, infrastructure, and private equity investment portfolios;

Supporting activities in any alternative asset class;

Ad hoc assignments.


Profile

*No visa sponsorship available for this position. Successful applicant will possess:


4-7 years progressive experience in real estate investments;

Understanding of real estate portfolio management, characteristics of the transactions and corresponding strategies, etc.;

Familiarity with real estate financial modelling and projection;

Highly motivated team player, with strong work ethic attention to detail;

Excellent verbal and written communication skills;

Superior academic achievement at a top tier undergraduate program. MBA and / or CFA is ideal.




Job Offer

Base salary + Performance bonus

The SEC is seeking the best and brightest to join our agency!


The position is in the Office of Compliance Inspections and Examinations located in New York, NY.

The Office of Compliance Inspections and Examinations ("OCIE") protects investors through administering the SEC's nationwide examination and inspection program. Examiners in Washington DC and in the Commission's 11 regional offices conduct examinations of the nation's registered entities, including broker-dealers, transfer agents, investment advisers, investment companies, the national securities exchanges, clearing agencies, SROs such as the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority("FINRA") and the Municipal Securities Rulemaking Board, and the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board ("PCAOB"). OCIE's mission is to protect investors, ensure market integrity and support responsible capital formation through risk-focused strategies that: (1) improve compliance;(2) prevent fraud; (3) monitor risk; and (4) inform policy. The examination program plays a critical role in encouraging compliance within the securities industry, which in turn also helps to protect investors and the securities markets generally.


If selected, you will join a well-respected team that is responsible for supporting OCIE's mission to conduct and coordinate the nationwide examination program for entities over which the Commission has regulatory authority.


Typical Duties Include:


In conjunction with the Assistant Director, planning, coordinating, and monitoring the activities and functions of the Clearance & Settlement (C&S) staff in their execution of clearing agency examinations and related activities;

Establishing and communicating examination goals, monitoring progress toward those goals, and ensuring compliance with National Examination Program’s  standards;

Providing guidance to the staff to ensure that deficiencies in statutory and regulatory requirements and other material weaknesses are identified through the examination process. Helping to manage and ensure quality and effectiveness of complex examinations, encouraging broad applications, and helping staff evaluate complex and sensitive issues;

Assisting in the collaboration with key stakeholders of the examination process, including internal divisions and offices (e.g. Division of Trading and Markets, Office of International Affairs), and other US and non-US regulatory bodies (e.g. U.S. Commodity Futures Trading Commission, Federal Reserve Board, Bank of England);

In conjunction with the Assistant Director, incorporating market and regulatory changes into examination activities.  Maintaining an up to date knowledge and understanding of current concerns for clearing agencies in the areas of credit, market, liquidity and operational risk.   Providing staff with information on industry trends, staff interpretations, and Commission announcements; and

Performing human resource management and administrative functions, relative to the staff supervised, in collaboration with the Assistant Director including: hiring and retaining staff, allocating work assignments, conducting performance evaluations, mentoring and training of staff.  Ensure established guidelines and performances expectations are communicated, understood, and followed by staff, which may include attorneys, securities examiners, accountants, and others.  Carry out Equal Employment Opportunities (EEO) policies, program, and diversity activities.


All qualification requirements must be met by the closing date of this announcement.

For full consideration, all applicants must apply online via the USAJobs link.
